storyPipeline.eventPlanUser:
Create nine chronological physical events from the literal seed.

Section hint: {{SECTION}}
Title: {{TITLE}}
Literal seed — this is the source of truth:
{{PROMPT}}
Editorial hints:
{{SEED_HINTS}}
Fixed cast — use only these people:
{{CAST}}
Previous recap for a sequel:
{{PREVIOUS_RECAP}}
Child's sequel choice:
{{CHOICE}}

Preserve the seed's exact activity, equipment, objects, animals, and location. Never replace or reinterpret an essential noun. Choose one concrete location and one visible final result. Then produce exactly three opening events, three middle events, and three ending events. Every event is one new visible action or observation in chronological order. Name the acting character and concrete object where useful. Opening events establish the exact equipment or object and begin the activity. Middle events continue the same activity through different actions without completing it. Ending events complete the activity through Glimsi's own action, make the visible result true, and let the same scene become still. Supporting characters may assist but never take over Glimsi's final action. Do not repeat an event with different wording. Do not invent a new hobby, journey, location, forced obstacle, failed attempt, unsafe action, puddle drinking, lesson, memory, future promise, or abstract emotional summary.

storyPipeline.proseActSystem:
You write one passage of a warm read-aloud story for children aged 4–8.
{{STORY_RULES}}
Write only natural past-tense story prose, with no title, heading, labels, or explanation. Narration carries the story. Dialogue appears occasionally when it feels natural.

storyPipeline.proseActUser:
Turn exactly these three planned events into one warm prose passage.

Stable story anchors:
{{STORY_ANCHORS}}

Previous ending — context only:
{{PREVIOUS_ENDING}}

Do not output, quote, paraphrase, summarize, or retell the previous ending.

Passage: {{PASSAGE_TITLE}}
Planned events, in required order:
{{EVENTS}}

Narrate all three events once and in order. Do not add another event, activity, object of focus, problem, location, memory, lesson, or future plan. You may add sensory detail, sentence rhythm, small gestures, and up to two short spoken lines. Attribute every spoken line with an explicit character name beside said, asked, or replied; never use a pronoun-only attribution. Write only as much as these events naturally need. Stop immediately after the third event.
